comments.text:
I'm 15, and here in Atlanta, we have quite a few gay people in our 
community, so you know they're all over the schools. Anyways, I have a gay 
friend (well, he's more of an acquaintance since I don't really talk to him 
outside of school). He acts masculine, doesn't USE the annoying high 
pitched girly voice, and dresses like a man, I guess. Anyways, once we were 
having a conversation, I expressed to him my feelings on homosexuality. I 
said I thought it was weird and don't really except it(I'm a christian, so 
since everyone is a sinner, I don't except what a LOT of people do in my 
school, smoking, drinking, premarital sex, etc., so he wasn't exclusive) . 
And you know what? He didn't care. He literally said IDGAF. It didn't 
really affect our relationship too much, cause EVERYONE has differences, 
and he acknowledge that. Everyone you meet in life will not agree with you, 
and that's okay. It's amazing how I have met and seen Jewish & christian 
friends, Jewish & Muslim, and even christian & atheist friends. They know 
they have differences and express them openly, but at the same time they 
don't let that affect their relationship and also can ignore those 
differences in certain situation.
The big problem I have in the gay community is not them being gay, but 
rather they FORCE their beliefs and views on to other. Live and let live. 
Everyone won't agree with you, and you know what? That's perfectly fine. 
But the minute you try to force you're belief system onto others, children, 
and also through television, movies, ads, social media, and everything in 
society in general, they aren't the bad one, YOU ARE. ﻿
